Sunny- no clouds- and wind variable at 0-2 mph- lake flys- gulls- ducks- cormorants. abundant filamentous algae on shore and bottom rocks  wet tree trunks are green with algae.
Very calm- high cirrus clouds admitting strong sunlight. floating filamentous algae and pieces of aquatic plants.
Sunny- southwest wind at 2 mph- and water surface scummy with filamentous algae. no blue green algae and very few daphnia.
Sunny and 3 mph southwest wind. high thin clouds. very few boats. wood ducks- cormorant. scum of dead insects- filamentous algae- no blue-greens- few daphnia.
Hazy- grey sky- and 3 mph southeast wind. 3 cormorants and gulls. many minute- unbranched filamentous algae.
Calm and hazy. thin clouds gone by 11: 00. no blue-greens- tiny daphnia.
Very light variable wind. broken clouds. 2 loons and 5 cormorants. curly leaf pondweed almost in flower at surface. abundant daphnia- microcystis- lyngbya- botryococcus- unknown alga.
Calm and sunny. 9 mallard ducklings. filamentous algae on plants- rocks and floating. conifer pollen. abundant plankton.
Sunny WSW wind at 10 mph. abundant blue-greens- daphnia- etc.- no ephippia! floating cut-up aquatic plants floating.
Calm with high humidity and the sunlight is dimmed by the hazy clouds. ewm almost to lake surface at north shore piers. unknown alga still very abundant.
Hazy sun and calm with west wind at 2 mph. no fragilaria in samples. blue-greens- etc. dispersed several inches below surface. floating pieces of aquatic plants and filamentous algae.
Hazy sun and south to southwest wind at 2-5 mph. motorboat slop. molted gull feathers. ewm abundant and near surface at piers. filamentous algae off aquatic plants but on shallow rocks.
Blue sky and large clouds- south and northeast variable winds at 0-5 mph. blue greens distributed several inches down shallow water clearing.
Sunny and southwest wind at 3 mph. floating gull feathers. "tapioca" bloom.
Sunny and variable wind from the northeast at 1-5 mph. most filamentous algae are gone from plants- rocks and lake bottom near shore.
Sunny and southeast wind at 4-5 mph. abundant plankton.
Sunny and calm with SSW variable winds.  Water clear in shallows- murky at end of pier.
Calm- some blue sky- hazy and sunny during monitoring. very few boats- 1 cormorant and flocks of gulls and cranes. fruits of sago pondweed and wild celery.
Low clouds- high humidity- and east wind at 3-4 mph. E wind 3-4 mph. floating wild celery. gull feathers and lady bugs.
Calm- east wind- and sunny. molted gull feathers. scummy with bloom. floating aquatic plants. coots and cormorants.
Sunny and west wind. thousands of gulls- 2 loons. floating wild celery.
Northwest wind very gentle and sun coming through the clouds. flocks of coots- 2 loons and floating gull feathers. no filamentous algae on plants or rocks.
Sunny and northeast wind at 5 mph. shallows very clear. sinking gull feathers. flocks of sandhills from 3 to 24 individuals. many ducks and gulls.
Hazy sun and south wind. Anabaena bloom- ladybugs and gull feathers. Flocks of coots on lake- geese flying over.

Variable winds and wispy clouds.  Lake s high as 6.8" of rain May 1-17.  Scummy surface:  Oscillatoria mats- fila algae- "junk"- conifer pollen- stellate hairs- no daphnia or cyclops- and two cormorants.  Air temperature is 73 degrees and water temperature is 64 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 4.0.

East wind calm at 8-10 mph. Clouds- cormorant- daphnia and cyclops present- and lots of floating debris on lake surface.  Air temperature is 61 degrees and water temperature is 58 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 5.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Calm and sunny.  Water clearer at MJB's pier- bed of Eurasian millfoil near surface- beds of p. crispus at Spg Grove- floating filamentous algae = spirogyra and zygnema- "cotton"- aquatic plants and dead insects and lyngbya.  Air temperature is 78 degrees and water temperature is 67 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Southwest wind at 7 mph.  Motorboat slop!  Many ephippia over lake surface at shallow and deep waters.  Air temperature is 84 degrees and water temperature is 68 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Sunny and east wind at 3-5 mph.  Clouds except for "center" of sky = Sun!  Floating clumps of filamentous algae and aquatic plants- beds of Eurasian milfoil- etc.- covered with filamentous algae- blue-greens now- and ephippia! Air temperature is 77 degrees and water temperature is 68 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny and variable wind at 2 mph.  Sunny!  Blue-green bloom- floating" broken aquatics- oscillatoria mats- filamentous mats of green algae + spirogyra and zygnema and black debris.  Air temperature is 86 degrees and water temperature is 76 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

North wind at 6 mph and sunny.  Clear water near pier- one carp- large school of 1" minnows off City- red admiral butterflies- and lots of plankton.  Air temperature is 74 degrees and water temperature is 73 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Calm and sunny.  Many ephippia- shallow at MJB's pier + clear water- minnows of bluegills and perch and carp.  Air temperature is 77 degrees and water temperature is 77 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 2.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Calm- sunny and humid.  Blue-green bloom- n o plankton tows- and monarch butterflies.  Air temperature is 84 degrees and water temperature is 82 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Hazy with light variable winds.  Motorboat slop!  Bloom!  Monarch butterflies.  Air temperature is 80 degrees and water temperature is 78 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Hot- humid- hazy and calm with 1-2 mph variable winds- large white clouds- variety of many blue-greens- greens- diatoms- desmids- dinoflagellates and invertebrates.  Air temperature is 88 degrees and water temperature is 83.5 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 3.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- SW wind at 10 mph- no plankton tow as too windy.  Female vallisneria flowers and long leaves = Forest Ave. and Sugar Loaf Harbor.  Complaints regarding aquatic plants and not enough harvesting for swimming. Air temperature is 82 degrees and water temperature is 75 degrees. Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- calm- variable wind at 1 mph- floating molted gull feathers.  Many ephippia from daphnia- MJB's pier visited by school of 2" minnows.  Air temperature is 80 degrees and water temperature is 78 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- hazy clouds- SW wind at 10mph- lake steamed early morning as 50 degrees temperature at night.  Drowning in Norwegian Bay.  Previous p. crispus areas = C demersum- vallisneria- EWM- H. dubia- and flat stemmed. Air temp is 80 and water temp is 74.5 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- north wind at 3-5 mph- sponges on aquatic plants floating past pier.  Floating = foam- torn-out and chopped up plants- many ephippia- oscillatoria mats and gull feathers.  Adult and immature loons.  Air temperature is 73 degrees and water temperature is 72 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

East wind at 8 mph- large clouds and blue sky.  Lake steamed in morning- geese flying over- many cut-up and pulled out macrophytes and no plankton tow.  Air temperature is 60 degrees and water temperature is 68 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

NW wind at 8 mph.  After cloudy morning- sun and large- low clouds- sick carp ( ) as on its side and going in circles.  Air temperature is 65 degrees and water temperature is 67 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 2.0 and at 2ft is 1.5.

Sunny and windless.  Bloom = anabaena- microcystis- lungbya.  Many bosmina!  Minnows at pier.  Gull feathers floating.  Coots arriving- three loons on lake- sandhill cranes and geese flying overhead.  Air temp is 67 and water temperature is 64 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny- high cirrus clouds.  SW wind at 7 mph at start and later dropped and variable.  Floating = foam- land vegetation (leaves) and clumps of aquatic plants.  East tow is much darker green than west.  Air temp 57 and water temp 58 degrees.  Color(custer) at 1/2 secchi is 4.0 and at 2ft is 2.0.

Sunny for monitoring but clouds- N wind ca. 4 mph. Frost last night. Gulls- 2 cormorants. Turbid water. Filamentous algae on rocks- plants- shallow to 8 feet+. Broken- floating aquatic plants.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 3; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 3; air temp = 55 F; surface temp = 48 F.

Sunny- blue sky- hazy with high cirrus clouds. No wind today; very windy yesterday. Floating fila. Algae- foam- white seeds. Fishermen hate the filamentous algae on their lines!  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 64.5 F; surface temp = 49 F.

Cloudless blue sky- very calm- light S but variable wind. BEAR reported! Flying geese; swimming duck family in middle of lake. Floating and attached filamentous algae = detrimental for fishing!  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 70 F; surface temp = 62 F.

Blue sky and calm water. P. crispus tops at surface. Observed floating Oscillatoria in east end. Abundant floating and attached algae.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 2; air temp = 72 F; surface temp = 66 F.

Sunny- calm. Clear water at N shore pier where aquatic plants grow low and few.  Floating clumps / pieces = fila. Algae- P. pectinatus- M. spicatum- Zannichellia- P. crispus- Ceratophyllum.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 3; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 2; air temp = 68 F; surface temp = 66 F.

Sunny- SW wind ca. 5-6 mph. East: Bluegreen bloom. Very clear water at N shore pier and area now thick with aq. Plants ca. 3-4 feet below surface- esp E. mifoil + P. crispus.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1; air temp = 80 F; surface temp = 70 F.

Sunny- hazy SW wind ca. 6 mph. Floating masses of chopped- broken aquatics. Many aq plants growing at piers (and deeper) in neighborhood.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1; air temp = 82 F; surface temp = 76 F.

Sunny- calm wind but motorboat slop. Aquatic plants near surface around piers; very clear water close to shore. Vacationers; telephone complaint re: very smelly fila algae washed ashore.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 99 F; surface temp = 79 F.
Sunny- light E wind. Days in 80's- nights cool. Bloom at N shore pier and cloudy water- 1 carp.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 3; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 73 F; surface temp = 76 F.

Sunny- hazy; light- variable wind. Many gulls at east inlet. Foamy surface with many floating- chopped aquatics.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 81 F; surface temp = 79 F.

Sunny- S wind ca. 3-4 mph. Blue-greens: Gleotrichia- Microcystis- Anabaena- Lyngbya and green = Botryococcus. Many colonial rotifers- Daphnia- Cyclops + nauplis.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 75 F; surface temp = 77 F.

Sunny- blue sky; wind SW ca. 8 mph. P. pectinatus fruiting. Masses of floating aquatic plants and masses growing in lake around piers.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 85 F; surface temp = 78 F.

Sunny- blue sky- wind SE ca. 3 mph. Nights ca. 50-60 degrees F. Many cut floating aq. Plants. Many piers are surrounded by very abundant macrophytes!  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 74 F; surface temp = 76 F.

Sunny- blue sky. W wind 8-10 mph. Very windy day before = gusts to 35 mph and water extremely turbid with sediments brought to surface from bottom. Vallisneria in bloom.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 86 F; surface temp = 76 F.

Sunny- calm!  Surface: foam and molted gull feathers- "Lady Bugs". Fish under pier = perch- blue gills. Gulls = 100's and 1 cormorant.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 3; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 85 F; surface temp = 76 F.
Sunny- calm- blue-green BLOOMS (see July 24).  Motorboat slop!  Low water level.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 85 F; surface temp = 76 F.

Sunny with clouds and very light- variable winds. Bloom! Feathers! Aquatic plants very abundant in neighborhood; children will not swim in them. Monarchs = 7 in 10 minutes.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 3; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 2; air temp = 88 F; surface temp = 78 F.

Sunny- quiet- very calm. Tornado = Ladysmith. Anabaena bloom E+W!  Floating: gull feathers- foam and aquatic plants. Tiny minnows- sizeable bluegills- perch under and along pier.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 79.5 F; surface temp = 75 F.

Sunny- but hazy. Calm. Monarchs- 1 loon- coots have arrived. Photos of Silver Creek Inlet: Eurasian Milfoil in flower and lily pads around piers. For many years- no aquatics evident!  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 93 F; surface temp = 78 F.

Sunny- light and variable winds. Aquatic plants at north shore pier down close to bottom- disintegrating. Fish around pier- bluegills- bass- minnows a few inches long. 3 carp cruising shore.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 83 F; surface temp = 73 F.

Sunny- NW wind ca. 3 mph. 100's of gulls and geese flying over. Aquatic plants disintegrating and down near bottom. Molted gull feathers!  Shallow water clar but at ca. 8 ft = turbid and green.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 2; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 1.5; air temp = 67 F; surface temp = 66 F.

Sunny- N wind ca. 3 mph. Floating = foam- land vegetation (leaves)- aquatic plants- Anabaena = minor bloom shallow- quiet water.  East station smells fishy. Loon- coots- gulls and 1 comorant.  Color (custer) @ 1/2 secchi = 4; Color (custer) @ 2 feet = 2; air temp = 54 F; surface temp = 59 F.
Cloudless blue sky- variable very light south wind.  Water murky after 4" rain in 2 days. Spirogyra abundant on surface- gulls- ducks.  Dandylion seeds floating on water.
Sunny- ESE wind at 3 mph.  Many small dead bugs- algae + P. Crispus floating.  On rocks: Spirogyra- Cladophora + Rhizoclonium.  Swallows nesting under piers.  No Lake Flies at Lake Winnebago.
Sunny and calm.  Out in lake- floating cut-off aquatics and algae.  Surface Spirogyra mats conjugating.  Hatch of tiny bugs.  Two loons. Gulls.
Hazy sun- variable wind to calm.  Terrible run-off Friday before this Sunday.  No bees observed on honeysuckle flowers today.
Thin clouds at west and sun at east end.  E wind ca. 6 dropping to 2 mph.  Daphnia in abundance.
Sunny and calm.  Geese. Floating in-lake west + east - pieces of M. spicatum- M. sibiricum- Ceratophyllum- P. crispus- green algae- locust flowers and seeds = dandylions- willows- cottonwoods.
Sunny but hazy clouds.  Calm- light S wind.  Shallow water = clear at pier.  Filamentous algae on rocks.
Sunny- cloudless with west wind 3-0 mph.  Ranunclus blooming at Mill pond.  Floating clump of aquatic plants torn out as roots present.  Ephippia abundant.  Filamentous algae on rocks = diminishing.
Sunny- variable light wind (3-1 mph) and motorboat slop.  Floating mats of aquatic plants- torn out/cut.  Debris from fireworks. Bluegreens like "tapioca" at both ends of the lake.
Hazy sun- partly cloudy- West wind at 4-6 mph.  Many floating masses of aquatic plants.  Plants at Heidel Bar almost to surface.
Sunny with NW wind. Clear lake water and very short aquatics at pier. Many aquatics visible out deeper and at "bars".  Surface water is green- "tapioca" with algal forms of many types.
Sunny and calm.  Gulls molting. Gleotrichia.
Sunny- light SW wind.  Gull feathers.  Monarch butterflies.
Hazy sun and clouds. Light variable wind. Gull feathers. Out in lake = foam on surface in several areas.
Sunny- calm with many clouds low in the sky.  Hundreds of gulls; 1 cormorant.
Sunny- clear sky- but hazy.  S wind ca. 8 mph. Lemna sp. out in lake at east end.  No plankton tow. Vallisneria female flowers.
Sunny- NE wind 4-6 mph.  Hundreds of gulls and floating feathers.  Dark green  = aquatics close to surface of lake at deeper water ("bars"- too) while light- yellow green masses = Mougiotia sp.
Sunny- south wind 6-8 mph. Bloom below surface.  Rocks- logs and areas with aquatics visible on bottom of lake ca. 10-15 ft. deep - and shallower of course.
Sunny- cloudless- SW wind 4-6 mph.  Pier monitor for zebra mussels = negative.  Lake clear. Gull feathers!  Duck flock (blue-winged teal ). Bees! Monarchs!  Carp!  Over 2.5 days = ca. 3.75" rain.
Sunny- cloudless. South wind 0-2 mph. Coots- other ducks- 1 monarch- many gulls and geese returning.  1 loon- mature Vallisneria- aquatic plants + Mougeotia on bars and ca. 10 ft. depth. Clear water!
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI

Air temp. 61 F- surface water temp. 53 F. Lake level 796.76 ft above sea level. Sunny- W @ 4-9 mph. Lake high + flooding! Lake = "chocolate milk". Dam repair needed 2005. (May 1-31 rainfall: City of Green Lake = 12.9"; Green Lake Sanitary District (GLSD) = 14.1")

Lake level 796.72 ft above sea level. Water color brown (custer @ 2 feet = 11 black). Perception 5 dirty. Air temp. 67 F- surface water temp. 62 F. Sunny- light variable wind. Lake = "dark chocolate" + Irving Park shore waters = brown with orange tinge (from soils in field above).

Lake level 796.52 ft. above sea level. Perception 5 (cold- dirty). Water color (custer @ 2 feet: 6.0). Air temp. 78 F- surface water temp. 70 F. Sunny- hazy- SE wind. Rain last night. Water so turbid. Noted filamentous algae not evident on plants + rocks as usual - this whole season. Daphnia first noted.
Color (custer @ 1/2 secchi: 2- custer @ 2 ft 1.5). Air temp. 72 F- surface water temp. 66 F. Sunny- very light SW wind. Floating Myriophyllum Spicatum.
GREEN LAKE AT GREEN HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI
Lake level 796.47 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 2- custer @ 2 ft: 1.5. Air temp. 75 F- Surface water temp. 66 F. Sunny- very light SW wind. Motorboat slop.
Lake level 796.46 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 1.5. Air temp. 67 F- surface water temp. 67 F. Sunny with clouds and gusty NW wind. Bloom.

Lake level 796.34 ft above sea level. Water color (eye) green/brown. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2. Air temp. 77 F- surface water temp. 72. Sunny- calm. Blue-green blooms- denser at East End. Many floating aquatic plants.
Lake level: 796.42 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2. Air temp. 83 F- surface water temp. 73 F. Sunny- calm. Blooms. Motorboat slop.
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI
Lake level 796.36 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2. Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 75 F. Sunny- calm. Hazy + cirrus clouds. Bloom- especially East End!

Lake level 796.30 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 2.5. Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 77 F. Sunny- calm. Bloom. Floating: aquatic plants- gull feathers and oscillatoria mats.

Lake level 796.26 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2. Air temp. 70 F- surface water temp. 76 F. Sunny- SW @ about 4 mph. Cool nights. Bloom. Surface foam. Gull feathers. Very abundant plankton collection!
Lake level 796.24 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2. Air temp. 70 F- surface water temp. 71 F. Sunny- calm. Bloom. Motorboat slop.
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI

Lake level 796.24 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 ft: 2. Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 72 F. Sunny- SW @ about 5 mph. Storms night before. Bloom. Rainfall: City = 1.2"; GLSD = 1.4".
Lake level 796.24 ft above sea level- custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 2. Air temp. 82 F- surface water temp. 74 F. Sunny- calm. Bloom. Clouds moving in. Floating gull feathers.

Lake level 796.16 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 2.0. Air temp. 80 F- surface water temp. 75 F. Sunny- calm. Floating: bloom- gull feathers- aquatic plants pulled out by roots and cut into pieces.
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI
Lake level 796.16 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 1.5. Air temp. 78 F- surface water temp. 70 F. Sunny- SE wind about 5 mph. Bloom. Coots. 2 monarch butterflies.
Lake level 796.12 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 1.5. Air temp. 81 F- surface water temp. 70 F. Sunny- light SW wind. Bloom. Butterflies: monarchs and yellow. Dragonfly.

Lake level 796.10 ft above sea level. Custer @ 1/2 secchi: 3- custer @ 2 feet: 1.5. Air temp. 74 F- surface water temp. 78 F. Sunny- light SW. Bloom. Lake at pier (north shore). Clear near shore but @ 8 ft depth only tops of aquatic plants visible. Coots- loon- monarchs.

Lake level 795.80 ft above sea level- custer @ 1/2 secchi: 4. Custer @ 2 ft: 1.5. Air temp. 72 F- surface water temp. 61 F. Sunny- NE about 3 mph. Coots- cormorant- gulls- loon- geese. Two Ephippia noted.
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI - SPRING CHEMISTRY

Sunny- large clouds- wind east 8 mph.  Green scum opening of Norweg. bay = 34 drowned flying insects- conifer pollen- stellate hairs- spirogyra- debris and many motile micro. cells.  Custer 1/2 secchi: 2.  Custer 2 feet: 2.  Air temp 70 F- surface temp. 54 F.

Sunny- calm- light variable wind.  Bloom at pier to shore- ca. 20 fish under pier.  Green- foamy scum on surface.  Filam algae at bottom + plants bothers fishermen!  First live Zebra Mussel found.  Custer 1/2 secchi: 3.  Custer 2 ft: 3.  air temp. 72 F- water temp. 64 F.

Hazy sun- light variable winds.  FLoating filam algae = Spirogyra and Cladophora.  Clearer in shallow.  Fish under pier.  East end especially scummy = floating seeds and terrestrial leaves.  First Daphnia seen.  Custer 1/2 secchi: 2.  Custer 2 ft: 2.  Air temp. 84 F and surface water temp. 74 F.

Sunny- calm- hot.  Very thick aq plants about 1 ft below surface at pier- mainly E milfoil.  Lake clear at pier.  Dozens of minnows and pan fish in area of pier.  Filam. algae on all rocks!  Custer at 1/2 secchi: 2.  Custer at 2 ft: 1.  Air temp. 91 F- water temp. 76 F.
Sunny with clouds.  Wind NE 5-8 mph.  No plankton tows as too rough.  Custer at 1/2 Secchi: 4.  Custer at 2 feet: 1.  Air temp. 72 F- water temp. 70 F.
GREEN LAKE AT DEEP HOLE NEAR GREEN LAKE WI

Sunny- calm.  Minnows and panfish at pier.  Thick aquatics at pier and all rocks from shore also covered with filam algae.  Many organisms of all types.  Smaple colors: East = green.  West = yellow.  Custer 1/2 secchi: 4.  Custer 2 ft: 1.  Air temp. 88 F- water temp. 77 F.

Cloudy- calm- humid.  East end: many ephippia on surface- murky and green.  Ranunculus in bloom near pier - even under lake surface.  Custer 1/2 secchi: 4.  Custer 2 ft: 1.  Air temp 78 F- water temp. 75 F.
Sunny- calm- wind NE ca. 4 mph.  Ephippia in samples only number 2 and 6.  Custer 1/2 secchi: 3.  Custer 2 ft: 1.5.  Air temp. 76 F. Water temp. 74 F.

Lake Level: 6.3 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1.5- air temperature (F): 81- Surface temperature (F): 70. Lake Level: 6.28 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1- air temperature (F): 75- Surface temperature (F): 71.  Sunny- hazy + partly cloudy. Red tops of Eurasian milfoil very abundant along shores and far out.

Lake Level: 6.22 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1- air temperature (F): 72- Surface temperature (F): 72.  Sunny- calm with light puffs of wind from north; later ca. 7 mph. Ceratium very abundant + many broken releasing yellow-gr blobs.

Lake Level: 6.15 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 3- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1.5- air temperature (F): 70- Surface temperature (F): 69.  Sunny + partly cloudy. Motorboat slop. Many fishing boats. Zebra Mussels obvious on shallow rocks. Wild celery floating in Dartford Bay Very abundant macrophytes all over + also cut-off + floating with white + fuzzy seeds- yellow particles + dead insects. New duckling parades out on lake.

Lake Level: 6.2 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1.5- air temperature (F): 77- Surface temperature (F): 73.  Sunny + dead- flat calm at west; when at east partly cloud and light wind.  AQWEED harvestor cutting in Malcolm Bay. Lake clear- no algae bloom.Aquatic plants too abundant in many areas- especially exotics- impairing activities in lake!

Lake Level: 6.17 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 2- air temperature (F): 73- Surface temperature (F): 70.  Sunny- partly cloudy. Floating gull feathers- foam + aquatic plant pieces. Micro.algal spp + invertebrates in suspension near surface. Carp- panfish.Large populations of zebra  mussels on rocks in shallow water.

Lake Level: 6.18 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 2- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1.5- air temperature (F): 76- Surface temperature (F): 74.  Sunny- wind NW 3-5 mph at west end.  Blue-green bloom where sheltered along north shore. At east end- too windy so no vertical plankton tow. Only WEST =++++: Anabaena flos-aqua- Chrysocapsa- Microcystis; +++: Gomphosphaeria; ++: Lyngbya bergei; +: Coelosphaerium + Gleocystis.

Lake Level: 6.08 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 3- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 2- air temperature (F): 61- Surface temperature (F): 71.  Sunny- partly cloudy. Calm at West; East is wavy + SE wind ca. 8 mph. Lake level low. Floating on lake are gull feathers- foam + cut aquatic plants.Recently night-time bow hunting for carp from lighted barge.

Lake Level: 6.02 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 2- air temperature (F): 69- Surface temperature (F): 71.  Partly sunny- West had variations in wind speed + direction- finally at East end it's calm. Floating clumps + pieces of aquatic plants- insects- gull feathers. Large flocks of gulls. Mallard ducks with growing families near City boats + beaches and along lake shore.

Lake Level: 5.98 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 3- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 1.5- air temperature (F): 69- Surface temperature (F): 71.  Sunny! Dead- flat calm. Low boating activity. Surface: some foam- MANY gull feathers- dead insects- cut macrophytes- light film of blue-greens. NOT a bloom.  HUGH Masses of gulls flying overhead along 23 between Ripon + Green Lake - for several miles.

Lake Level: 5.94 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 2- air temperature (F): 73- Surface temperature (F): 72.  Sunny- little or no wind for a week. Low lake level.  Floating on lake: cut-up and /or pulled-out aquatic plants- MANY gull feathers- terrestrial leaves+ Duck Weed (Lemna minor L.) originating in Silver Creek NOW out on lake!

Lake Level: 5.9 feet- Custer Colors (1/2 Secchi): 4- (1/2 M or 2 Feet): 2- air temperature (F): 73- Surface temperature (F): 74.  Another sunny- calm day! Floating on lake are aquatics (Vallisneria) sometimes enclosing Duck Weed- gull feathers- foam + dead insects. Lake level low! Many fishing boats. Zebra Mussels obvious on shallow rocks. Wild celery floating in masses in Dartford Bay. AQWEED closed Labor Day.

Water VERY turbid and stragly "blurry". Floating filamentous algae: bg Oscillatoria + grs Cladophora- Spirogyra- Zygnema. Many Diatoms- No macrophytes or fish at my north shore pier. Floating maple seeds- catkins- pieces of leaves- insect bodies + white seed filaments.

Diatoms: Asterionella- Synedra- Tabrllaria spp- Lake not comparable to any (Custer) color; West=whitish + East = whitish + East = orangish. No bg or gr a Zooplankton: abundant Cyclops- Naupli- 1 Asplanchna; Rotifers are Filinia- Keratella spp. Swallows eating lake flies. Few gulls- 1 cormorant

1st Daphnia noted- + MANY Bosima- Cyclops and Nauplii. 1st Ceratium. Green Algal spp.: Coelastrum- Colacium- Mesotaenium- Pediastr Spirogyra. Conifer pollwn (yellow)- Locust trees blooming. Ducklings. Lake still blurry colors and turbid.

High W winds day before + now floating broken-off Eurasian milfoil + foam. Harvesting at Spring Grove. Carp and other fish evident. Two more gr Algae: Zygnema + Scenedesmus + unknown. Still no bg algae. Daphnia infrequent. Active "eyeless" planaria.

Lake is clearer. Abundant zooplankton + important from now on. 1st bg is Gleocystis. Very thick mat of gr filamentous algaa Rhizoclonium covers littoral zones in some areas ca. 1 m below lake surface. Few gulls. Lots of gr fila. algae attached to piers- plants + rocks.

Daphnia e phippia (resting stage) obvious in surface scum. Ranunclus in bloom. Macrophytes showing thru the mat of Rhizoclonium espe but most buried by thick mat. 5 bg algae spp. + 6 gr algae spp. present now. Many floating broken macrophytes + algae clumps.

Rhizoclonium astonishing in its abundance + smothering macrophytes along some shores. Many comments on this unusual condition. In some places excess aqautics around piers with harvesting program advising of overtime work

Found 8 spp bg + 8 spp. gr algae bt dinoflagellate Ceratium is the most abundant (+ from now on!). Rhizoclonium mat covers rocks- Lake clearing. Floating gulls' molted feathers- cut-off macrophytes + filamentous algae. 1 carp at pier- 1 loon on lake
Duckweed and some watermeal becoming nuisance entering via Silver Creek. Thick mat of Rhizoclonium very unusual + still evident.

Turbidity increasing. Plankton show 6 spp bg and 9 spp gr algae . ZM v's = ABUNDANT- showing active cilia + movements of whole organisms- sometimes spinning. Two high- circling flocks of whote pelicans. Rhizoclounium sample sent to DNR

Lake scummy but not a serious bg bloom. Looks like "tapioca" distributed throughout top few inches. Wind is 4-8 mph. West end's water is unusal yello-w-green (Custers color 6). BG algae: Anabaena- Gomphosphaeria- Microcystics- Coelospheriaum- Lyngbya- Gleotrichia + Oscillatoria. More Ceratium than any other taxa. ZM v's at ABUNDANT level. Perception of lake water qaulity is poor.

Previous filamentous gr. algae attached to shallow water rocks + are gone except for fringe of Cladophora at edge. Macrophytes not visible at pier. Floating cut mcarophytes- duckweed and molted gull feathers. ZM v's = Very Abundant.

Foating cut macrophytes- molted gull feathers- duckweed and slight scum on surface and below. Many female flowers of Vallisneria + tall P. pectinatus with 1 flower/fruit. Monarchs and yellow + white cabbage butterflies. No macrophytes around pier. ZM v's ABUNDANT

Lake is very green and murky. Floating cut-off aquatic plants- duckweed- foam and molted gull feathers. Valisneria flowers + fruits. Still no obvious aqautic plants near pier. Fishing guide caught lake trout with bite makes. Monarchs- many gulls + 1 loon. ZM v's almost gone.

Adult ZM's very obvious on rocks 1-2 m. Lake has "tapioca/pollen" look. Morphos migrating- cabbage butterflies and birds flocking on land. Floating cut-off/torn-out macrophytes- dead insects- an apple- seeds- leaves + molted gull feathers. Last time microscopic ZM v's noticed.

Algae: bg. Anabaena- Coelosphaerium- Gomphospheria- Microcystiis + Lyngbya; grs = Sphaerocytis- Botryococcus- Crucigenia- Ocystis Little Gr. balls.  Very Abundant: Ceratium- Fragillaria- Vorticella- Staurastrum + Zooplankton. Rotifers: Collotheca- K. cochlearis + Polyarthitias

Clear lake near pier showing many adult zebra mussels on most rocks and very few + short macrophytes (Najas Flexilix  ). Visible particle on surface water but not a bloom. MANY gulls (molted feathers)- mallards- coots- 1 loon with geese + cranes flying over.

Deep-water clearing and 1/2 Secchi shows green colors. Sonde however- shows zero turbidity from 2-25 m except East's 25 m. Plankton samples are very thick. At many Secchi disk readings I notice a green mass hovers to envelop disk just below readings.

Unusual lake colors of  brown- red + yellow. Murky lake scummy with insects- seeds from cotton woods and other trees. Locust trees blooming. No macrophytes visible at north shore pier but some cut + floating. Filamentous algae attached to shallow rocks. No plankton tow or probe today.

Secchi + Custer Colors are blurry to me and lake colors via eyes are green-brown West end and green-brown + red at East. Murky lake and surface has floating seeds and insects. No plankton tow and probe today. Gulls not observed. Do not nest at Green Lake.

Pier area murky and short tufts of algae on rocks; no macrophytes visible. Floating pulled-out macro- clumps of algae- foam- dead insects and terrestrial seeds.  Very abun. Conochilus + Keratella spp. No blue-greens- infrequent greens + abund. Fragilaria- zoopankton + Ceratium.

Clear at north shore pier: 7 carp- 1 bass + blue-gills visible. Cladophora fringe on shore rocks. Filmentous floating algae are Rhizoclonium + Oscillatoria. Dark green Cladophora mat solid to 1.5m. + diverse macrophytes visible off pier now. MANY Daphnia Ephippia floating all over lake! 	Blue-greens appearing and 3 days later (July 6) formed a mild BLOOM. Both plankton samples had reddish globs. Only 1 ZMv.

Slight bloom of blue-greens: High to low + alph.: Anabaena- Microcystis- Coelosphaerium- Gleocystis- Lyngbya- Oscillatoris + Gomphosphaeria. Ceratium is Most Abundant of ALL from now on. Ranunculus blooming. Abundant numbers of velligers of ZMs and Ephippia of Daphnia
East end unusually clearer than West end. East end had many Ephippia floating on surface. No plankton tows. Hydrolab (probe) only West as by that time too windy.

column2: Slight bloom of blue-greens (etc.) scattered through lake surface. High to low + alpha.: Anabaena- Microcystis- Coelosphaerium- Gleotrichia- Gomphosphaeria- Lyngbya + Oscillatoria. MANY greens- ZMv- Zooplankton while only 1 Ephippia in East + West. Monarchs- loon- gulls + vultures.

column1: Air Temp. = 88 degrees F

column2: Motor boat slop! Slight BLOOM of blue-greens-etc.- scattered through lake surface. Gulls VERY abundant + molting feathers! Monarch butterfly flying SW over lake. Very Abund. Ceratium- Zooplankton and velligers of ZMs. New blue-green  = Nodularia ( ).

column1: Air Temp. = 76 degrees F

column2: No plankton tow. Monitoring data completed.

column2: Unusual abund. of Dinobryon again! Usual blue-greens (see above). Greens: Botryococcus- Coelastrum. Oocystis- Sphaerocystis ( )- Crucigenia- Gloecystis- Pediastrum- Urogleopsis ( ) + Little Green Balls. Did not find: ZMv- ephippia of Daphnia- Egg clusters of Cyclops.

column1: Air Temp. = 59 degrees F
Water Temp. = 64 degrees F

column2: Second calm day. Blue-green bloom: Anabaena- Microcystis + Coelosphaerium. "Watermeal" present. Flock of coots- 3 separate loons- 3 cranes-

column1: many gull feathers- foam + clumps of floating macrophytes. Micro. view of samples show usual: many pieces of plankton and also fibers.
Air Temp. = 75 degrees F
Water Temp. = 63 degrees F

column2: Lake level 6.58 feet; Air temperature 71 F.  Water temperature 64 F.  After recent deluges- observed floating debris of all sizes plus floating mats of Spirogyra + Ulothrix.Terrible transparency today and 19th.

column1: Some green algae but mainly diatoms. No sign of macrophytes off north shore pier; pan fish and minnows present. No gulls. No ZM v's.

column2: Deep-water still turbid and "blurrie" with a strange whiteness noticed other years and also now in Silver Creek channel + Beyers' Cove. Few green algal species- diatoms plus Cyclops- Nauplii + counted 2 Daphnia = sign of clearing lake soon! Rotifers abundant- no blue green algae.  Air Temp. 77 degrees- Lake Surface Temp. 60 degrees.

Lake clearer! Diverse- abundant macrophytes nearing surface at north shore pier: Eurasian milfoil- curly-leaf pondweed + rampant zebra mussels (ZM) on rocks. Filamentous green algal spp. attached to EVERYTHING! Many green and first BG algae observed. Air Temp. 68 degrees F- Lake Surface Temp. 68 degrees F.

Lake clear! but green at 1/2 secchi. Very abundant zooplankton + ephippia of Daphnia are floating all over lake's surface (not dangerous). Dartford Bay's floating filamentous algae: Zygnema- Spirogyra- Cladophora + Rhizoclonium. Four Blue-green's present now; not in bloom. Air temp. 80 degrees F. Lake surface temp. 72 degrees F.

Ranunculus in flower. Very abundant diverse macrophytes covered with massive filamentous green algae visible in littoral zone! Not swimmable at many piers and difficult for boats! Finally ZM v's abundant under microscope. Clear at west end but murky at east end. Air temp. 82 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 73 degrees F.

Macrophytes = many piers not swimmable. BG's (alpha.): Anabana- Chroococcus- Coelosphaerium- Gleocapsa- Gomphosphaeria- Lyngbya- Microcystis- Oscillatoria Spp. floating mainly below surface (like "tapioca"). Gulls + ducks present. Basswood flowers/seeds falling.Air temp. 82 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 73 degrees F.

From now on Ceratium is most abundant plankton. Eight BG spp (see 06/28/2012 data for list) + about nin green algae species. Some piers not swimmable but temperature grand for swimmers. Informed no AQWEED- Inc. harvester coming to lake until July 16 and GLSD sold transport barge in 2011. Macro. covered by filamentous algae: abundant Zygnema- some Spirogyra- Cladophora + Rhizocolium Spp. Zooplankton + ZM v's abundant. Air temp. 79 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 82 degrees.

Many macrophytes covered heavily with species listed in 07//08/2012 comments section. From now on- observed fila. empty of centents. Pier not swimmable. Floating are Oscillatoria mats (looking like "turds")- molted gull feathers- torn out macrophytes- filamentous algae clumps- dead insects and basswood tree's fruit/seeds. Usual green algae (alpha.): Botryococcus- Coelastrum- little green balls- Oocystis- Pediastrum- Rhizoclonium- Sphaerocystis + Spirogyra Spp. Abun.: Diatoms: Asterionella + Fragilaria; Desmid: Staurastrum. Air temp. 90 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 84 degrees F.

Native macro. are VERY abundant and fruiting; dense beds of wild celery! Fila.  algae prominent in bottom mats and attached to macro. One BG Aphanizomenon; Anabaena + Macrocystis = Very abundant- no bloom. Pseudodendromonas attached to Cyclops. Pelican flock circling. Air temp.73 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 78 degrees F.

Northshore pier's macro. harvested - finally. Fila. algae declining! Plankton similar to "Tapioca" lumps floating below surface- Gleotrichia evident. Some Certium broken. Some fila. algae without contents. Pseudodendromonas on dead Cyclops. Microscope view of ZM v's identified. Air temp. 86 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 80 degrees F.

Rain caused problems. Native aquatic plants abundant with flowers + seeds all over lake in littoral zone + fila. algae declining. Microscope view of ZM v's identified. Air temp. 78 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 73 degrees F.

No BG bloom but slight surface skim of Anabaena. Other abun. BG's: Gleotrichia- Lyngbya + Nodularia. Native aquatic plants flowering and fruiting abundant. Earlier large masses of fila. algae gone from rocks + plants. Floating molted gull feathers- algae and aquatics. Abundant ZM v's. Air temp. 78 degrees F- Lake surface temp. 73 degrees F.

Large number of gulls- molting feathers. Many floating torn-out wild celery plants as roots are never securely attached- some turning brown as they decay. Natives and algae same as in 08/19/2012 comments section. Still fila- algae strands without contents observed. Air temp. 84 degrees- Lake surface temp. 76 degrees.

No blue-green bloom but skim of Anabaena. Microscope shows Gleotrichia "nibbled". Still female flowers of wild celery + floating minute white "boats" carrying pollen observed. Many gulls- ducks and one loon. Air temp. 80 degrees F- lake surface temp. 76 degrees F.

NO PLANK. TOW. Macrophytes diverse and no pier problems. Filam. algae decline! Flowering wild celery VERY ABUNDANT + tiny "boats" of pollen on lake surface. Low water level = massive beds of this macro!!! Some floating macro surrounded by foam (decaying!) Floating gull feathers. Coots in Dartford Bay. Air temp. 80 degrees F- LAke surface temp. 72 degrees F.

Few rare sterile rushes emerging near road at Maplewood; photo 12 Sept. 1998 shows very abundant then. Identified as Sagittaria cuneata Sheldon ( ) by Neil Harriman (OSH)- common name is Arum-leaved arrowhead. Turkey vultures + huge numbers of gulls. Coots- sandhill cranes- turkeys- ducks and geese acrive. Low lake results in many floating- broken- decaying macrophytes + scummy with dead insects- seeds and leaves. Air temp. 60 degrees F- lake surface temp. 62 degrees F
Cloudy and calm- so not good monitoring weather. Surface scummy with bugs and many seeds from land plants- the dandylions and cottonwoods. Honeysuckle- locust trees and dame rockets blooming.

column1: ` Some Spirogyra conjugating.

column2: Finally excellent monitoring conditions with sun- a few white clouds and wind ca. 5 mph. Also motor boat fixed helped! North shore pier showed beds of Eurasian milfoil coming near surface in clear lake. Usually macrophytes diverse there.

column1: Floating mats of cut-off macrophytes included: Lemna spp.- attached filamentous algae (Spirogyra- (conjugation observed) Zygnema- Rhizoclonium + Cladophora) + abundant cottonwood seeds often colored some contents of mats white. Floating Lemna spp evident at East end surface.
Sugar Loaf cove showing almost entirely Eurasian milfoil and an impressive school of minnows!

column2: Excellent day: calm and sunny! Macrophytes coming toward surface with some filamentous algae attached.
Excellent day: calm and sunny although we started out with clouds! Macrophytes growing toward and on surface with some filamentous algae attached.

column1: Flowers/seeds for exotic Eurasian milfoil (unusual in Green Lake)- and natives Ranunculus (white flowers of Buttercup) + Potamogeton pectinatus (looking like small beads on a string for Sago Pondweed).
Variety of visible blue-green algae scattered down several inches below lake surface. Not a ?bloom?.
Some torn-out-by-boats floating mats of macrophytes- seed filaments- insects- and filamentous algae- etc.

column2: Hazy sun found between clouds- with light wind from SW dropping to very light variable wind. Macrophytes growing toward and on surface with filamentous algae attached. Motorboat slop. One loon- gulls- flying hatches of insects- grasshoppers- fireflies and damsel- and dragon-flies.

column1: Some flowers/seeds found on few broken off exotic Eurasian milfoil plants- as well as natives Ranunculus (white flowers of Buttercup) and Potamogeton pectinatus (looking like small beads on a string for Sago Pondweed). White water lilies blooming in Mill Pond on very abundant plants.
Variety of visible blue-green algae particles scattered down several inches below lake surface ? especially in East. Not a ?bloom?.
Some torn-out-by-boats floating mats of macrophytes- seed filaments- insects- and filamentous algae- etc. Terrestrial trees are fruiting.

column2: Sunny- dead- flat calm and any wind light and variable. Macrophytes growing toward and on surface with filamentous algae attached. Motorboat slop. Variety of visible blue-green algae scattered down several inches below lake surface ? especially in East - and along shore. Not a ?bloom?.

column1: Floating mats of macrophytes- seed filaments- insects- and green filamentous algae includes Zygnema- Spirogyra- Mougeotia. Attached to many submersed aquatic plants are large clumps + webs of green filamentous alga sp. Rhizoclonium as well as small quantities of the above green algae.

column2: Sunny with clouds and calm with very light variable wind. Activity of boats of all varieties and motorboat slop was especially bad! Macrophytes growing thickly toward and floating on surface with attached filamentous algae (Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra). Many more gulls appearing- several hatches of insects- grasshoppers- fireflies and damsel- and dragonflies. Very few butterflies noted.

column1: Variety of visible blue-green algae- etc. scattered down several inches below lake surface ? especially in East.
Not a ?bloom?.
Yesterday - due to wind and waves - the lake was very dirty - apparently with suspended sediments - and many aquatic plants floating and attached near pier impeded swimming enjoyment.

column2: Sunny- hazy- partly cloudy with light SW wind ca. 4 mph. Surface has foam- molted gull feathers- floating clumps of macrophytes ?sometimes looking a little like the ?Sargasso Sea? - along the shore out about pier length and between neighborhood piers definitely impeding swimmers. Blue-greens near surface are Anabaena- Microcystis and Gleotrichia- especially the latter- showing in the East end. This variety of visible plankton- some also listed below- are scattered on and down several inches below lake surface.

column1: Macrophytes growing thickly toward surface between and far out from piers are covered with very large quantities of attached filamentous algae. These are Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra + especially Rhizoclonium. Alga forming a fringe along rocks at lake waterline is Cladophora.

Vallisneria is appearing among other macrophytes on the bottom of the lake in the littoral zone. With boating activity- this native plant - with its small roots and long leaves and flower stalks- - is very easily pulled out- floats and becomes very messy. Their floating masses have been observed decaying on lake surface on hot- sunny days other years.

column2: Sunny and calm at start. Wind changed from East to North increasing at East end to about 5 mph. Not very good sailing that weekend for sailing regatta.

column1: Blue-greens near surface and below surface ? like ?tapioca? - but not a bloom.
No plankton tow and no Custer Colors.

column2: Sunny and calm with very light variable winds. Surface has foam- molted gull feathers- floating clumps of macrophytes ?sometimes looking a little like the ?Sargasso Sea? - along the shore out about pier length and between neighborhood piers definitely impeding swimmers. Blue-greens near surface are Anabaena- Microcystis and Gleotrichia- especially the latter- showing in the East end and a faint scum Anabaena. Otherwise the variety of visible plankton- some also listed below- are scattered on and down several inches below lake surface.

column1: Macrophytes growing thickly toward surface between and far out from piers are covered with very large quantities of attached filamentous algae. These are Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra + especially Rhizoclonium. Alga forming a fringe along rocks at lake waterline is Cladophora.

Vallisneria leaves are nearing surface but so far no signs of flowers on their spiral ?stalks? or the floating ?boats? carrying pollen formed underwater among the roots of the native plant known as Wild Celery.

column2: Sunny with dead- flat calm today. Many- many gulls have arrived. Surface has foam- molted gull feathers- floating clumps of macrophytes. Saw wonderful large school of minnows near surface at east deep-water station. Noticed 3 carp and 3 pan fish at pier. Wild celery leaves (Vallisneria) appearing very often in littoral zone all over lake. Macrophytes are growing thickly toward littoral zone surface between and far out from piers and are covered with very large quantities of attached filamentous algae: Zygnema- Mougeotia- Spirogyra + especially Rhizoclonium. Duck weed and skim of Anabaena floating at surface at west station today - probably because so calm.

column1: Recently the harvester came to my pier while I was on the pier and I watched it go around the pier area as DNR recommends. After the harvester left- the weeds were still thick- tall and covered with same thick algae. The mess of thick plants and algae seemed to rise up again and were not improved by the presence of the harvester. (Photo taken) The harvester should have accumulated a large- heavy load of aquatic plants just at my pier with the quantity of them we have this summer. The harvester visit was very disappointing. Perhaps heavy algal quantity is causing problems with unsuccessful cutting through aquatic plants? (macrophytes?) stems.

Will a new harvester be able to cut deeper? And unload onto the transport barge when cutting very large quantities of weeds? Problems persist and abound for the use of this lake for those who live here and wish to use it for their enjoyment. Boat navigation in some places on lake is difficult due to weeds- too- resulting in motor problems.

column2: Sunny and hot out here on the lake! Calm but terrible motor-boat-slop as a Saturday!

column1: Wonderful minnows visible in deep water near surface at east end and also out away from north shore pier. Fishermen are reporting minnows all over the lake and seeking official identification. Unofficially may be shiners of some sort.

Many years ago- emerald green shiners were present around piers throughout lake; one could net bait for fishing easily off piers. One year they all died out possibly due to some chemical impacting the lake water.

Noticed masses of bright green filamentous algae with some bubbles of oxygen covering macrophytes along north shore and these masses are very easily dispersed- i.e.- are past their prime. The main algal species noticed are Mougeotia (some conjugation observed)- Rhizoclonium- Spirogyra and Ulothrix.

Aquatic plants now showing their tops with fruits through the algae are many Long-leaf pondweed (Potamogeton nodosus) and a few Clasping?leaf pondweed (Potamogeton richardsonii). Wild celery (Vallisneria americana) is also abundant. Eurasian milfoil seemed underneath the algal masses in these locations along north shore.

I observed one monarch butterfly flying over the lake surface heading south west and was pleased to hear of a friend who saw more than 30 over several days of driving in this area and toward Fox Lake.

column2: Today is partly cloudy- with low + variable winds. Terrible motor-boat-slop as a Saturday!

column1: The East Secchi is very unusual and I may have been in an area that was stirred up for some reason. I should have moved and tried it again.
Unknown minnows in a large school visible again near surface in deep-water. Large masses of floating aquatic plants! One monarch butterfly is seen flying over lake.

Today it is strange that so very few Daphnia + Cyclops are evident in the two samples of plankton tows at both East and West as these critters are usually very visible in samples via eyes. A fishing guide believes these two listed above show up on his depth finder at 30 feet and the bluegills are at a level below them. I would like to go deeper with the plankton net for a more satisfying ?picture?. I wonder if this observation will happen again.

column2: Sky is sunny with no clouds and lake is dead-flat calm. Many of the floating weeds are in mats and some mats are looking brown as though plants are decaying. Wild celery floating in Dartford Bay along the shore often has bubbles around their masses and I do not know exactly what it means but possibly more decaying.

column1: Many molted gull feathers floating on surface from the many gulls. West end had many small insects flying just over surface and dead ones forming a scum on the lake while East end had no insects evident at this time. Faint Anabaena scum (as so calm) and many plankton + blue-greens forming ?Tapioca? appearance several inches below surface at both ends.
Three flocks of coots are on lake and a larger flock is in Dartford Bay.
Mimic shiners spotted at East end today.

The filamentous algae are gone. Perhaps the windy days have helped this happen. What has happened to them? From my slowly moving boat- the shallow water of the littoral zone is very clear on this calm day revealing sandy and stony areas among the aquatic plants. This clear view of the bottom has not been visible for weeks because of the thick filamentous algae covering the massive macrophytes during this season earlier.
Now Eurasian milfoil has mainly empty stems with a few leaves near their tops just below the surface.
Many small-sized shells of dead zebra mussels are visible lying on the bottom as well as live ones attached to hard surfaces and to some aquatic plants.

column2: Zooplankton- phytoplankton- chlorophyll- and pH data also collected
Zooplankton- phytoplankton- chlorophyll- and pH data also collected
Zooplankton- phytoplankton- chlorophyll- and pH data also collected
Zooplankton- phytoplankton- chlorophyll- and pH data also collected

day was very cloudy with variable wind at ca. 5- 8 MPH

25 was dead-flat calm and sunny- perfect for all the other monitoring: the plankton tow- Secchi + temperatures. Many gulls and many floating molted feathers on surface as well as pulled-out aquatic plants (espec. Vallisneria) and algae blooms with East end worse =  (?tapioca?= larger colonies visible in the lake water). Perhaps the lack of waves and wind did not mix?up the algae bloom to make it less noticeable.

column1: Flying monarch butterflies evident as well as coots- other ducks- cranes + geese with turkeys + many deer in area

column2: Air temperature 63 F; Very unusual to see school of 36 carp at north shore pier.  Lake very calm and water murky and green brown.  No blue-green (BG) algae observed. Turbidity definitely not working as 0.0 from surface to 25 m.

Air temp 74 F- Even though CLEAR recorded in deep-water stations + Secchi  at its deepest for this season at 32 + 38 ft- at ladders of many piers are very abundant in weeds.  Still no BG algae observed.  Plenty of zooplankton- green algae- Ceratium- a few diatoms- golden + protozoa.

Air temperature 80 F- Floating filamentous algae (greens); Spirogyra- Mougeotia- Ulothrix- Zygnema.  Flowering macrophytes are in Pondweed group: clasping-leaf- Sago + invader Curly-leaf.  Deep-water + shallow areas are clear.  Taxa are: BG's #4- greens #8- diatons # 4- + Daphnia very active with Ephipp(ia?) (resting stage of D.) Many other plankton observed.

Air temp 70 F; Ranunculus in bloom. Same four filamentous algae (see above) floating and attached to plants.  Blue-greens; Gloeotrichia- Microcystis- Anabaer(a?)- flos aqua- Coelastrum- Chrococcus + Gleocapsa are floating at + below water surface. Ceratium most abundant- very active and broken.

East end (4) worse than west end (3) according to My Perception. First time I observed ZM Velligers (immature zebra mussels).  Ceratium still most abundant. 7 BGs- 8 greens- + many others listed in 5th report.
Air temp 64F; East is still worse than west in My Perception.  Abundant plankton is suspended under surface of water + down to 17 ft.

Air temperature 88 F- Molted gull feathers floating + plankton are visible and are distributed high and low in the upper lake water.  Ceratium most abundant of all. ZM Velligers abundant. Many fibers observed. Unknown filamentous green algae conjugating with zygospores.  Marl appearing on weeds.

Air temperature 78F; Many floating molted gull feathers- foam- pulled out + cut up weeds- especially wild celery. Floating duckweed is at east end coming from Silver Creek inlet.  Some empty filamentous algae. Ceratium most abundant- also Vorticella + Binobryon are abundant.  Many plankton taxa!

Air temp 80 F; BG Anabaena spp. + Microcystis spp. are very abundant. Ceratium and Vorticella are abundant. ZM Velligers infrequent today.  East end (4) is worse than the west end (3) in My Perception + Secchi shows this- too.  Duckweed + watermeal into lake from Silver Creek via east winds. Minnows at n. shore pier. Many pieces of plants + animals- debris- fibers + terrestrial seeds in tows.

Air temp 80 F; Lake water very green but not a bloom (wind?).  Many gulls + floating molted feathers. Both West + East are poor (4) in My Perception + Secchi di(?) is 8.0 ft at both.  Many plankton but Cyclops and Daphnia are infrequent.  No ZM velligers observed today.

Air temp 80F; Surface foam from motor boat activity- molted feathers from gulls- and many cut macrophytes floating as growing close to surface now. Wild celery female flowers on their spiral stems visible above their thick mats of leaves.  No Daphnia observed at and above plankton tow.

column1: Depths of 2- 5- 10- 15- 20- and 25 ft.

column2: Air temp 69 F; Female flowers of wild celery are nearing surface + masses of weeds with large amount of filamentous algae visible.  Two carp: one natural and one Koi-like.  No Daphnia observed. Infrequent Cyclops and ZM velligers.  Lake is green in color.

Air temp 77F; Slight surface skim of light green color is BG anabaena. Many pulled out and chopped up weeds + attached aquatic weeds still heavy with filamentous algae.  No Daphnia but abundant ZM velligers.

Air temp 51F; Anabaena flos aqua is thick showing down below surface several feet at east end resulting in terrible Anabaena bloom.  No Daphnia + infrequent (dead) Cyclops.  Previous large quantities of filamentous algae found on bottom and weeds seem reduced to me. Near pier are school of minnows feeding on the surface and 8 nice-sized fish with dark tails. Dissolved Oxygen is very good from 2-25 M (high winds for days). Very abundant beside BG above (see June 29) are Vorticella- Golenkinia (in clusters)- Dinobryon + Polyarthra.

column1: Depths of 2- 5- 10- 15- 20- 25 feet

column2: Lake water very brown. Two hugh schools of minnows in shallow + deeper around pier + several carp! No BG algae.

column1: Some Fragillaria + Staurastrum while G- filamentous algae are mainly Cladophora + Spirogyra. Many Zooplankton:
Keratella spp.- Kellicotia- Bosmina- Daphnia + Cyclops. Masses of land seeds- small black solids some very sharp (=Echino-
sphaerella limnetica?)

column2: Murky lake surface scummy with dead insects and terrrestrial seeds. Macrophytes not visible. Two hugh schools of minnows

column1: + evidence of carp spawning near pier with one large (female) followed closely by several smaller carp (males). BG:
Lyngbya + Oscillatoria; G: Spirogyra- Cladophora- Botryococcus- Pediastrum; ZOO: see above plus Conochilus unicornis +
many Nauplii; DIAT: Fragillaria- Navicula- Stephanodiscus + Asterionella. Conifer pollen- pieces of plants + animals- debris!

column2: Lake clearing + no BG's or weeds evident. Ceratium present for 1st time + also ZOO more than  Leptodorus + Polyarthra. Colonies

column1: of Conochilus unicornis very abund. as are minnows at many piers. Tons of floating dead + decaying carp killed as prevented
spawning by higher fence at West estuary (Hghy K). Today SE shore's bed of curly-leaf pondweed is being harvested.

column2: Lake water very clear showing zebra mussels growing on rocks in shallow water and 1st micro view of a ZMv.* BG:

column1: Gleotrichia- Gloeocapsa- Microcystis + Oscillatoria; G: have 10 different spp. Many floating- dead carp + many minnows.
East wind pushed duckweed + common watermeal out on lake from Silver Creek. Wild celery beds seen up from bottom.

column2: No minnows observed today. Motorboat slop as many boats + water is murky. Weeds close to surface along north shore.

column1: Daphnidia showing resting stage (=Ephippia). ZMv + Ceratium are abundant. Still many dead carp - especially on east shore.
Vultures picking dead carp to bones while other animals ate bodies leaving the scales/skin on the shores. Smelly!

column2: Lake very murky with skim of BG at surface + visible down several inches: Anabaena flos aqua- Gleotrichia echinulata plus 7

column1: more spp.; ALL G: Sphaerocystis-Chlorophyta- Coelastrum- Gloeocystis- Oocystis- Bortyococcus- Mouteotia + unknown.
Gulls abundant and molted feathers show up from now on.

column2: Some flowers of wild celery at surface as are many other weeds. Many gulls + their floating- molted feathers present. Very

column1: abundant: BG: Anabaena spp- Gleotrichia- Microcystis (+8 spp); G: Sphaerocystis (+11); Dino: Ceratium (+5); DIA: Fragil-;
laria (+1); DES: Staurastrum (+1); + ZOO: ZM v's- Keratella cochleari (+9). Unknown filaments- debris- pieces of P's + A's.

column2: At surface are wild celery flowers and many other taxa of weeds so it's impossible to use ladders + swim at piers. Only

column1: areas where motorboats are moved in and out of piers are the weeds lacking. Floating weeds are also a nuisance.

column2: Serious quantities of weeds growing in littoral zone often torn off + floating.

column1: Today minnows at piers again + noticed 2 cormorants- 2nd batch of ducklings + floating molted gull feathers.
NOTE: (1) Anabaena flos aqua- (2) A. helicoidea  (regularly coiled) + (3) a very straight A. sp. I called Nodulalria ? previously.

column2: Many floating + growing native weeds- some filamentous algae + MANY wild celery fruits forming. Gulls very abundant- flock

column1: pelicans high over lake- 2 cormorants + at pier were school of minnows- one carp + several panfish. ALL BG: Anabaena spp.-
Gleotrichia spp.- Microcystis spp.- Aphanocapsa- Aphanotheca- Chroococcus- Coelosphaerium- Gleocapsa- Oscillatoria +
Gomphosphaeria. ROT.:  Keratella cochlearis- Conochilis unicornis- Colotheca (no tube)  + Polyarthra.

column2: Two monarch butterflies- many gulls- line of 8 carp cruised past pier this week. Many torn-out macrophytes floating - mainly

column1: native. Small flock of coots in Dartford Bay. No plankton tow today.

column2: East station has a very scummy and colorful surface compared to West station. One monarch butterfly observed

column1: over lake today + 7 observed earlier in week on drive to Berlin.  Most Abun. BG Algae: Anabaena flos aqua- Coelosphaerium-
Microcystis spp.; G: Gloecystis; Dino+Proto.: Ceratium- Vorticella; DIA.: Fragillaria; Des + GOL: Cosmarium +
Desmidium; ZOO.: Cyclops + Daphnia + ROT.: Polyarthra

column2: The lake is brownish with large amounts of filamentous algae floating along the shores and strands growing up from the bottom in littoral zone.

column1: ONLY West station sampled as forgot sample bottles so estimated quantities may be off or missing.  Abun. GR: Spirogyra + BG: Oscillatoria.
DI: Stephanodiscus- Fragillaria- Tabellaria spp; DE: Staurastrum; ZOO: Abun. Cyclops (eggs)- Nauplius + Keratella cochlearis.
Conifer pollen evident. Hydrolab did not register Turbidity today but resumed next time out.
First day out trying HYDROLAB- Secchi disk- Custer Colors and plankton tow- the latter only minimal EAST sampled due to missing collection containers. No WEST sample taken at all.
Today is sunny with cool- light NE wind. High cirrus clouds with cloud bank far to the south.
Along shore are narrow band of thick floating algae and a small sample showed mainly green algal species Spirogyra (some conjugation starting) + very small amount of blue-green algal Oscillatoria.
Diatoms- Cyclops and Nauplii are especially abundant.

column2: Thick floating algae are very extensive along shore and also small patches far away from shore. GR: abun. Spirogyra; BG: infreq.

column1: Oscillatoria-  DI: Asterionella- Fragilaria- Pennales- Cyclotella- Stephanodiscus + Tabularia spp.; GO: pres: Dinobryon- ZOO: abun. Cyclops (eggs)
Nauplii- Asplanchna- Keratella quadrata (eggs)- K. cochlearis (eggs)- Kellicotia + Polyarthra.
ALWAYS SEEN ARE: pieces of plants + animals- unknown filaments + debris and- now- floating conifer pollen. Turbidity of  0.0 (NYU) is
common in deeper water in Green Lake. Sometimes sharp- black objects with no apparent cells visible (Echinosphaerella limnetica?)
Today lake is dead- flat calm with partly cloudy sky. Sun seems very warm when present.

Thick floating algae are more extensive as observed along shore and also small patches far away from shore. As before these are mainly the green algal species Spirogyra (conjugation starting) + smaller amounts of the blue-green algae Oscillatoria.
Today lake is dead- flat calm with partly cloudy sky. Sun seems very warm when present.

Thick floating algae are more extensive as observed along shore and also small patches far away from shore. As before these are mainly the green algal species Spirogyra (conjugation starting) + smaller amounts of the blue-green algae Oscillatoria.

column2: Today lake is dead- flat calm with partly cloudy sky. Sun seems very warm when present.

column1: Thick floating algae are more extensive as observed along shore and also small patches far away from shore. As before these are mainly the green algal species Spirogyra (conjugation starting) + smaller amounts of the blue-green algae Oscillatoria.

column2: Today?s North wind varied from ca. 7 ? 2 mph and sky is partly cloudy.

column1: Unlike previous thick floating algae only a very few  tufts of floating Spirogyra were observed.
Also sampled were rocks in shallow water where abundant Cladophora + some Rhizocolium appeared.

column2: Today?s wind is SWW- quite strong but no white caps and sky is practically cloudless.

column1: Surface of lake is very scummy with previous floating-through-the air seeds- tree droppings and many tiny insects.  No weeds are visible in the lake at this time but occasional deep clumps of filamentous algae in shallow areas. Note the weed harvester is located behind island at Hattie Sherwood Park now.
Not a bird seen out on lake today but 3 cormorants were observed last time out.

column2: Surface of lake is very murky and scummy with seeds- tree droppings + many tiny insects. East end has unusual watery brown Custer Color that I

column1: never noticed before + I called it a "BROWN #2" *. No weeds visible at surface but occasional deep clumps of filamentous algae in shallow areas.
No blue-greens observed today. GR: very abun: Cladophora- Spirogyra; infreq: Pediastrum + Ulothrix. DI:pres. Ceratium (first time evident).
DI: Very abun: Asterionella- Fragilaria; infreq:Pennales- Melosira- Cyclotella- Stephanodiscus + other Centrales. DE: pres. are Cosmarium- Synura
+ unknown strands. ZOO:very abun. Cyclops (eggs)  + Bosmina (eggs) + showing up at last are a few Daphnidia in the 17 ft. samples.
Very abu: Keratella cochlearis (eggs)- K. quadrata (eggs) and infreq are Kellicotia (males + females). Day before monitoring was VERY windy
+  noted MANY oak leaf stellate hairs which have been present previously in smaller numbers.  (* Custer Color #2 is a watery- clear soft green).

column2: Lake is murky- green-brown- and very scummy (see above) + also with foam + Lemna. Today observed no macrophytes + no BG plankton.

column1: Clumps of GR very abun. filamentous algae (Spirogyra + Rizeclonium)are in shallows and floating + Cladophora is attached to rocks at shoreline.
DI: Ceratium + PRO: Vorticella both infreq as are DI: Stephanodiscus + other Centrales while Fragillaria is abun. + many are broken.
DE: one Staurastrum + abun. unknown strands. ZOO: Very Abun.: Cyclopoids (eggs); small Bosnia + Daphnidia; Keratella cochlearis (eggs)-
K. quadrata (eggs); Nauplii are infreq. + only 1 each for Leptodora + Kellicotia (egg). Many very active = zoospores? + oak leaf stellate hairs.
Observed in samples are epiphytes on plankton- pieces of plants + animals- debris - especially tree droppings + terrestial seeds - + conifer pollen.
Partly cloudy- light variable winds at West Station + dead flat calm at East Station.

Surface of lake is very scummy with previous floating-through-the-air seeds- tree droppings and many tiny insects.  No weeds are visible in the lake at this time but occasional deep clumps of filamentous algae in shallow areas and floating filamentous algae. Many small insects seen hatching- circling in the air - land + water.
Swallows flying near piers and parade of a family of geese near Malcolm Bay. Ducks in bay and along shores.

column2: Clearer water in shallow areas and deep-water Secchi. Custer color at East station is unusual Irredescent Green (#6) at 1/2 M. GR filamentous

column1: algae seems reduced and macrophytes are now sparse + not close to surface. BG: Abun: Gleotrichia echinulata- Gomphospheria + Microcystis spp.
GR Abun. Pediastrum- Spirogyra + one Scenesdesmus longus. DIN.: Abun Ceratium + PROT. Stentor + Vorticella in very few numbers.
DIA: very abun are Fragilaria; abun. are Stephanodiscus and infreq are Asterionella. DES: abun. Staurastrum- unknown strands + one Closterium.
ZOO: Very Abun. Bosmina- Naupli + Daphnidia; Abun. Cyclops- Keratella spp.;  Few: Conochilus unicornis- Kellicotia + Polyarthra.
NOTE:  Daphnidia show Ephippia so entering their "resting stage". Many eggs + egg clusters visible. Two examp. of single pollen grains germinating.

Today?s wind changed from very light to actually dead-flat-calm at west end- but later at the east end was about 5 mph from the SW. The sky had many interesting clouds and some blue sky - so partly cloudy.

Surface of lake in some places showed cottonwood seeds and foam. The ?tapioca look? of many particles distributed through several inches down from the surface at east end as blue-greens appear - plus pollen- pieces of leaves. duckweed- etc.  White water lily is in bloom in Mill Pond.
Very dirty water in lake due to Monday?s storm run-off and lots of tree damage.  By Wednesday- today- lake was much clearer than previously!  Not so much filamentous algae present as seen earlier.
The tops of a few scattered weeds are visible in the lake now that clearer water present.
Zebra mussels are not especially obvious on bottom rocks or ladders in shallow areas.

Very tiny- new minnows are in a school at a north side pier in shallow water; also present are blue-gills- carp + bass. New ducklings in Dartford Bay area and many other birds ? parents and juveniles - abound in our yards- woods and along waterfronts.
I heard that - many minnows present during 2016-17 winter?s fishing all - over the lake.

column2: Today?s wind changed from light SW- to about 8 mph  SW. The sky had many interesting clouds and some blue sky - so partly cloudy.  Motorboat slop was as expected on the lake near the 4th.

column1: Surface of lake in some places showed cottonwood seeds and foam. MANY  particles (blue-green algae) distributed through several inches down from the surface - especially at east end.

Near piers tops of a few scattered weeds are visible in the lake now that clearer water present.  Some have filamentous algae on their tops. Thick beds of weeds are almost to the surface out in deeper water.
A few gulls are present and a family of geese seen at Sugar Loaf.

column2: The sky is partly cloudy- the wind very light (SE) + terrible blue-green scum by afternoon! Dead-flat calm does help the bloom situation!

column1: Floating are patches of filamentous green algae (Spirogyra + Zygnema) mixed with broken-off weeds.	Weeds covered with filamentous algae are becoming evident at ladder of pier + VERY evident when moving boat over deeper water. Gulls are more abundant + a first molted feathers seen from them.

column2: Sunny and SW wind ca. 8 mph with high cirrus and a few other clouds at the horizon.  It is a very lovely summer day with little boating activity.

column1: The lake water is very clear near my pier along the shore and I could see the carp with an orange pectoral fin and head ? much larger now than previous years when it has appeared in my area.

The wind today and over the last few days may have distributed the blue-greens to other depths (see Turbidity on page 2).  Previously (at bottom of Report #10 and 2 days after monitoring) when the east wind had piled up the blue-greens so pea soup developed and the bottom/fish- etc- were unseen! I was shocked! 	Sunny and SW wind ca. 8 mph with high cirrus and a few other clouds at the horizon.  It is a very lovely summer day with little boating activity.
The lake water is very clear near my pier along the shore and I could see the carp with an orange pectoral fin and head ? much larger now than previous years when it has appeared in my area.

The wind today and over the last few days may have distributed the blue-greens to other depths (see Turbidity on page 2).  Previously (at bottom of Report #10 and 2 days after monitoring) when the east wind had piled up the blue-greens so pea soup developed and the bottom/fish- etc- were unseen! I was shocked!

column2: Today is sunny with few clouds and NE wind ca. 7 mph.

column1: The lake water is very clear near my pier along the north shore with no fish visible while on the pier at various times today. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake. Each 17 ft. vertical plankton net sample is VERY GREEN and full of zoo- and phyto-plankton! MANY OF THE BLUE-GREENS ARE TOXIC TO DOGS- HUMANS AND OTHER ANIMALS?

Checking the cove at Sugar Loaf I found many tiny white female flowers of Vallisneria (wild-celery) blooming above lake and below are their very abundant leaves. A few mature clumps of Potamogeton pectinatus (Sago Pondweed) are also visible near surface and Eurasian milfoil- of course.

At my north shore pier- besides the above weeds- are several large clumps of Heteranthia dubia (water-stargrass) and lots of Eurasian milfoil. All are often supporting filamentous algae containing mainly Spirogyra + some Mougeotia. Cladophora grows on the rocks along the shore.  Gulls are more abundant now adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements. Foam is often on the water.

column2: Today is sunny with clouds and light NE wind which diminished to nothing and increased again.

column1: The lake water is quite clear near my pier along the north shore with only very small black minnows visible. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) are hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake. Each 17 ft. vertical plankton net sample is VERY GREEN and full of zoo- and phyto-plankton!
Gulls are more abundant (counted ca. 70 on canopy- end of pier and float at a neighbor?s waterfront one day) adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements.
Foam is often on the water with torn-out weeds. Weeds + filamentous algae are getting close to the surface at many piers.

column2: Today is sunny with no clouds and mainly dead-flat calm.

column1: The lake water is quite clear near my pier along the north shore with very small black minnows anad shiners visible. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) are hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake. Each 17 ft. vertical plankton net sample is not either as green and or as full of zoo- and phytoplankton as seen previously this season!
Gulls are very abundant adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements.  One merganser and many ducks noticed; some coots are present now.

Foam is often on the water with torn-out weeds ? especially wild celery leaves. Fruits are now forming on some masses of wild celery; now would be a good time for a harvester to move in and control some of this nuisance plant?s population by removing their obvious turions!

column2: Today is sunny with no clouds and mainly dead-flat calm.

column1: The lake water is quite clear near my pier along the north shore + no fish observed. Many particles (mainly blue-greens) are hovering in the upper surface of the water column throughout the lake
Floating weeds are mainly wild celery with foam usually present; fruits observed on many.
Both 17 ft. vertical plankton net samples are again not as green or as full of zoo- and phytoplankton as earlier this summer.
Gulls are very abundant adding nutrients to the lake by their many molted feathers and their excrements.  Three merganser and many local ducks (mallards) noticed; some coots are present now.

column2: Sunny and SW wind ca. 8 mph with no clouds visible and little boating activity. The wind velocity increased by at the east end of lake.

column1: The lake water is very clear near my pier along the shore and I could see no fish. Lots of foam on the lake- often in streaks and wind has piled small clumps on the shore. Also foam is very pronounced around masses of floating weeds. Observed many gulls on lake and also large masses of coots now gathering along lake?s shores and Dartford Bay.

Duckweed is floating on surface in several large masses at eastern part of lake probably moving back to their main source- Silver Creek estuary after several days of northeast winds. Perhaps because of the increased wind at east end and the duckweed- the lake appeared murky there.
